body:
This isssue is somewhat weirder than the previous ones. The following example 

```systemverilog
interface I;
  logic foo;
endinterface

module M0;
  logic foo;
  initial begin
    foo = 1;
  end
  I C();
  assign C.foo = foo;
endmodule

module test;
  M0 C();
  task automatic bar(virtual I C);
  endtask
  initial begin
    bar(C.C);
  end
endmodule
```

issues a combinaional loop warning:

```
%Error: bug.sv:11:16: Wire inputs its own output, creating circular logic (wire x=x)
   11 |   assign C.foo = foo;
      |                ^
%Warning-UNOPTFLAT: bug.sv:6:9: Signal unoptimizable: Circular combinational logic: 'test.C.foo'
    6 |   logic foo;
      |         ^~~
                    ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/UNOPTFLAT?v=5.027
                    ... Use "/* verilator lint_off UNOPTFLAT */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
                    bug.sv:6:9:      Example path: test.C.foo
                    bug.sv:11:16:      Example path: ASSIGNW
                    bug.sv:6:9:      Example path: test.C.foo
%Error: Exiting due to 1 error(s), 1 warning(s)
```

However, if I change the name of the formal parameter `C` of the task `bar` to `D`, the message disappears.

```systemverilog
interface I;
  logic foo;
endinterface

module M0;
  logic foo;
  initial begin
    foo = 1;
  end
  I C();
  assign C.foo = foo;
endmodule

module test;
  M0 C();
  task automatic bar(virtual I /* only change is from C to D */ D); 
  endtask
  initial begin
    bar(C.C);
  end
endmodule
```

In addition, if, when the formal parameter is named `C`, I change the signal `M0.foo` to a different name, say, `baz`, 

```systemverilog
interface I;
  logic foo;
endinterface

module M0;
  logic baz; // changed foo to baz
  initial begin
    baz = 1;
  end
  I C();
  assign C.foo = baz;
endmodule

module test;
  M0 C();
  task automatic bar(virtual I C); 
  endtask
  initial begin
    bar(C.C);
  end
endmodule
```

Verilator issues another error, which can be resolved by changing the name of the formal paramter to another name.

```
%Error: bug.sv:11:12: Can't find definition of 'foo' in dotted signal: 'test__DOT__C.foo'
   11 |   assign C.foo = baz;
      |            ^~~
        ... Known scopes under 'foo': C
%Error: Verilator internal fault, sorry. Suggest trying --debug --gdbbt
```

> What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

`verilator --timing --trace --top-module test--binary bug.sv`

> What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?

Tried on Verilator 5.026 and current git master.

> What OS and distribution are you using?

Ubuntu 22.04 under WSL.

> May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

If this look like someone who is a Verilator beginner could reasonably handle.
